    <item>
      <title>The Conquest of Sloth</title>
      <description>Today&apos;s story will change how you see everything... In the ancient forest of Naimisha, the great sage Narada was said to have encountered a young prince named Nishadha, who lived in a world of perpetual sleep. Nishadha&apos;s kingdom was once prosperous, but as he succumbed to the sin of Sloth, his people began to suffer. They toiled in darkness, their crops withered, and their children cried out for the love and attention they deserved. Narada, moved by their plight, shared a parable with Nishadha about the tree that withered and died for lack of rain. Nishadha laughed at the tale, believing that he, the lord of the land, was above such petty worries. But Narada revealed the truth: a king who neglects his duties is like a tree that fails to bend in the wind. The people of Nishadha&apos;s kingdom suffered, and the prince himself became a shadow of his former self. This is Sloth — the belief that your own greatness is too great to be bound by the needs of others. Ask yourself, how much longer will you sleep, and how many lives will be lost because of your inaction?</description>
